function numMusicPlaylists(n, goal, k) {
    const MOD = 1_000_000_007;
    const dp = Array.from({ length: goal + 1 }, () => Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => 0));
    dp[0][0] = 1;
    for (let i = 1; i <= goal; i++) {
        for (let j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
            dp[i][j] = ((dp[i - 1][j - 1] * (n - (j - 1))) % MOD + (dp[i - 1][j] * Math.max(0, j - k)) % MOD) % MOD;
        }
    }
    return dp[goal][n];
}
```

    Here, we use a Dynamic Programming approach to solve the problem. We first create a 2D array dp where dp[i][j] represents the number of playlists of length i formed using j different songs. We initialize dp[0][0] to 1.

Then, we loop through each cell of the dp array from length 1 to goal and from song 1 to n. For each cell, we do the following:
1. Add a new song to the playlist. The number of ways to do this is (n - (j - 1)).
2. Add an existing song to the playlist, with the condition that the song is not played in the last k positions. The number of ways to do this is max(0, j - k).

We add both of these to update the value of dp[i][j] and calculate the result modulo 109 + 7. Eventually, we return the value in dp[goal][n] which is the number of possible playlists of length goal formed using n different songs.

